{
  "answer": "The Persianate title *Bang-e-Dara* (\"The Sound/Call of the Marching Bell\") commits Iqbal to a classical Perso-Islamic poetic motif: the caravan bell (*bang*) as a resonant summons (*dara*, evoking march/journey) for awakening, movement, and communal destiny—imagery rooted in Sufi and ghazal traditions of existential pilgrimage (e.g., Rumi's caravan metaphors).[^1] An Urdu title, by contrast, would likely evoke more vernacular, localized intimacy (e.g., folksy *ghanti ki awaaz* or *safar ka ghunghru*), lacking this elevated, pan-Islamic register that frames Iqbal's Urdu nazms/ghazals as a prophetic call to a slumbering *ummah* (Muslim collectivity) to mobilize.[^2]\n\nThis commitment does real work in \"Tarana-e-Milli\" (\"The Anthem of the Community\"), the collection's nationalist crescendo, where Iqbal's own song becomes \"the marching bell's refrain\" explicitly rallying the global Muslim \"caravan\" onward.[^3]\n\n[^1]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 1*, Ch. 5 (\"Kahoon kya aarzoo-e be-dili mujh ko kahan tak hai\"), [para. p-7f2bca](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c/05-kahoon-kya-aarzoo-e-be-dili-mujh-ko-kahan-tak-hai/translation/#p-7f2bca). The poet self-identifies as this latent bell, silenced until the caravan stirs.\n\n[^2]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 3*, Ch. 4 (\"Dil se jo baat nikalti hai asar rakhti hai\"), [para. p-ee2a79](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-3-cc61e8/04-dil-se-jo-baat-nikalti-hai-asar-rakhti-hai/translation/#p-ee2a79). Here, the *ummah* is the unstoppable caravan whose \"only baggage is a single bell, / A cry to march.\"\n\n[^3]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 3*, Ch. 23 (\"Tarana-e-Milli\"), [para. p-852c70](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-3-cc61e8/23-tarana-e-milli/translation/#p-852c70).",
